Palestine responds to Israel: We will break up any agreements that have been made so far.
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas announced on Thursday at the UN General Assembly that he would break all agreements with Israel if the future government tried to comply with Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement of the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
"If the future government of Israel stands up to implement this plan, we will invalidate all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made," he announced.
“We will reject the whole plan completely and completely”, he threatened with Abbas’ pressure.
"It is our duty to defend all of our rights by all possible means – it is of little importance to what will be the consequences – fully committed to the application of international law and to the fight against terrorism," declared the President of the Palestinian Authority, who has already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, the former prime minister of Israel, was reinstated after the 17 September elections.
One week before the election, he announced that if he won, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank in Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by Jaser Arafat, signed a number of peace agreements with the United States.
The 84-year-old Abbas also promised at the session of the UN General Assembly the holding of universal elections on Palestinian soils.
The last was held in 2006.
"After returning to the country, I will call on the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem local elections, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community," the Palestinian president declared solemnly.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer in the United Nations, to exercise the powers conferred on “full-fledged members of the United Nations and all its organs and institutions”.
The Palestinian leader concluded his speech by calling on the international community “to force Israel to comply fully with the United Nations provisions”.
Ambassador Danny Danon of Israel replied briefly to Abbas, stating that the Palestinian leader “will want to focus on the efforts of the Palestinian Authority against Israel, rather than to fight against the calls for terrorism in Autonomy under his leadership”.
However, according to the agencies, Danon did not refer to Netanyahu’s foretold annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
