PLN 105 million for companies in the field of video games from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will reach companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced on Friday the results of the III edition of GameINN.
Almost 30 projects supported by NCBR included developing a platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine creating a map of the real world together with an application for data transmission by users; a test-based training platform to verify the practical skills of VR and AI jobs; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using a innovative playing model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the industrial 4.0 concept – the NCB communication sent on Friday's PAP.
The aim of the GameINN Sector Programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry in the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 was PLN 1.85 billion and the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared GameINN research agenda and already reaching 300 million PLN support for entrepreneurs under this sector programme are an important impetus for further, dynamic growth of Polish gamedev," we read in the Communication.
Video games industry is an excellent example of the efficient use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The government's incentives for innovation entrepreneurs, such as B+Rs, competence improvement programmes, IP boxes or support programmes implemented by the NCBRs drive innovative companies and enable them to compete more effectively in a highly competitive market," said Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The Head of Science points out that innovation money not only reaches innovators in the form of project funding, but also remains in their pockets – from relief to R & D in 2018 three quarters more entrepreneurs than a year earlier.
‘The amount of the deductible costs for R & D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which provided more than PLN 300 million for companies benefiting from this benefit.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in the three editions of GameINN", stressed the Deputy Prime Minister.
In addition, the Director of the NCBR, Dr. Wojciech Kamietski, recalls that in the two previous funding competitions with a total value of more than PLN 211.2 million, 78 innovative projects were awarded.
The huge interest of the III competition and the diversity of the applications submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and enhance its competitive advantages.
"It is generally a pleasure to see projects identified, as in previous editions, with projects dealing not only with entertainment but also with Industry 4.0," he adds.
In the third GameINN contest for financing up to 20 million PLN, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia of entrepreneurs with scientific entities could apply.
The NCBs received 87 applications for a total of approximately PLN 317 million.
The budget of the contest at the time the contest was announced was PLN 100 million, but it was increased so that 27 projects were granted almost PLN 105 million of funding.
Detailed information on the results of the GameINN III contest is available on the web site cncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN Sector Programme is implemented under the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
The NCBR launched the programme in 2016 in response to the initiative of business associates associated with the Polish Games Agreement, which includes, among others, CD companies such as Project, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
