President of Iran says he refused to speak to the US, Donald Trump denies
Tehran did not speak to the American side during the UN General Assembly in New York, despite the American offer of lifting sanctions, President Hassan Rowhani of Iran announced on Friday.
U.S. President Donald Trump commented that the Iranian side had asked for the abolition of the restrictions, which he did not agree to.
According to President Hassan Rowhani of Iran, Americans have proposed the abolition of all sanctions imposed on Tehran in exchange for negotiating a new international agreement.
It would regulate both the Iranian nuclear programme and the ballistic missile programme.
Rawhani: Iran will not hold talks in the atmosphere of maximum pressure
The President of Iran stated that he did not agree to these discussions because of the “toxic atmosphere”.
He announced that he had met with American diplomats because he had been called France, Germany, and Great Britain.
However, he stressed that Iran would not engage in talks in the atmosphere of "maximum pressure".
"Even if we want to negotiate with the Americans in 5+1, no one is able to predict what the final outcome will be," Rowhani said.
The day before, the Iranian leader said that he did not exclude talks with the US and that the European parties to the nuclear treaty had rejected favourable US sanctions on Iran.
He added that the sanctions imposed on Iran following the appearance of the US with a nuclear contract “are a prerequisite which does not allow” to establish dialogue.
If we can overcome this prerequisite and if America lifts the sanctions and maximum pressure, then of course we can talk to America – he declared.
He added that he did not rule out a meeting with President Donald Trump of the United States, although he did not agree to such a conversation during the week during the UN General Assembly.
Trump: "Iran asked, I said no."
Donald Trump wrote on Twitter that he refused to ask the Iranian side.
"Iran wanted me to lift the sanctions imposed on them so that we could meet.
Of course I said no!" the president of the United States tweeted.
Voltage with atomic agreement in the background
France, Germany and the United Kingdom are trying to alleviate tensions between Washington and Tehran in some form to save the 2015 Iran agreement, which was signed by the signatories.
In exchange for lifting the economic sanctions, Iran was to abandon the nuclear weapons programme and the nuclear sector would be subject to the control of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
Since the withdrawal of the US from the agreement in May 2015, its signatories have repeatedly confirmed that they want to keep the agreement in force.
So far, none of this has worked.
Washington is applying a policy of exerting maximum pressure on Iran, and sanctions include a full embargo on Iranian oil.
Tehran announced that if it did not receive a permit to export raw materials, it would limit its obligations as a result of the agreement every 60 days.
