“42% of the species of trees on the European tree are at risk”, warns the International Conservation Union (IUCN) in the "Red Book of European Trees" published on Friday.
There are, among other things, chestnuts and berries at the top of the list.
IUCN, a organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was drawn up by specialists who, based on research, concluded that out of the 454 species of trees found in Europe (as well as in other parts of the world), 42% are "highly endangered".
Among the causes of the Red Paper is the rapid expansion of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that exist only or mainly on our continent.
With regard to the typical European treeland, 58% of the species are at risk, and 15 percent, 66 species of trees and shrubs, according to IUCN experts, are threatened with extinction.
Among the main causes of the deforestation, the book mentions errors in logging operations, accelerated urbanization, too intense tree cutting, and further forest fires and changes in European ecosystems.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, flies and grasslands is also severely threatened.
"The consequences of human activities lead to the gradual decline of species of European plants and pose a danger in Europe to the disappearance of important and underestimated varieties, which form the basis of European ecosystems and affect the health of our planet," said Luc Bas, who is leading the IUCN European office.
