"Positivity": Ignoreing the officer's order will be punished
According to the paper, disregarding the order of conduct issued by a police officer is to be a new type of offence at risk of fines, arrest or restriction of liberty.
Introducing such a change would be wanted by police liaisons.
The idea reached the Commission's meeting on Petitions.
"The matter is serious, because now more than half a million cases are being brought to the Polish courts every year," we read.
The Commission found that a petition, which the Independent Police Association is writing to Members on the amendment of the Code of Offences, has a chance to succeed.
The petitioners propose a new wording for Article 54a of the Code of Offences.
It should read: “Whoever does not obey the request or command of a public official issued within the limits and under the provisions of the law shall be punished by the arrest, fine or restriction of liberty.”
“Par. 3 of this provision speaks of the same punishment for those who do not follow orders, prevent or hinder the performance of their work”, the journal says.
Socjolog Andrzej Kowalski said "The Red Cross" that although he agreed with the main message of the proposal, he was afraid that if implemented, he could be used in political demonstrations.
"In situations of free demonstrations, it would be disadvantageous and instead of mitigating the situation, would exacerbate it," he adds.
Statistics given by the newspaper show that 86% of citizens have been positive about police interventions in 2018 and that 1.5 million interventions in the city are carried out each month.
