Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to Thomas Cook bankruptcy
Although Thomas Cook's British travel agency has fallen, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is functioning.
However, the company has problems.
According to VRT, Brussels Airlines announced that they were canceling 105 flights in October due to Thomas Cook’s bankruptcy problems.
Neckermann also fired 75 employees.
All trips with the office, which have been reserved in Belgium, will be cancelled, but temporary officials will be able to receive a refund.
The Gandawa court also announced the collapse of three Belgian subsidiaries: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently around 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips bought by Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were supposed to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, Empress Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said that the company is now "full operational" despite the British parent company's announcement of bankruptcy, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office calmed down that the customers who bought the tours would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the world's largest travel agencies – announced a fall on Sunday night on Monday.
The direct cause of bankruptcy was the collapse on Sunday of the last chance with creditors and potential investors.
In addition to an agreed rescue plan already agreed in August of £900 million, the creditors demanded that the company obtain an additional 200 million as a security for the winter period when the travel agencies usually had lower turnovers.
However, the company’s problems have been growing for several years, with a debt of 1.6 billion pounds.
