Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – this unique offer has been prepared for the arrival of the German Görlitz.
Actions are designed to help combat the progressive decline in the population.
Görlitz is the most prominent city in Germany to the east.
The beautiful pastel old lady attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, as The Guardian writes, the city faces considerable problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city also faces a permanent decline in the population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the western part of the country, which changed to a decline of 25% in the city’s population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000 people.
To fight the population, officials came up with an idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been submitted to the programme.
Two thirds of them were made up by residents of large cities.
The programme was also of interest to people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
"When we applied, we thought the program should convince people to move to Görlitz," one of the project participants said.
"Now we feel that it doesn't matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand free apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the average in the whole country.
While the city authorities hope that some will be held permanently, the main objective of the programme is to get the opinion of the participants.
Information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to learn more about what people need, and if they decide to move – what their motivation was," Robert Knippschild said.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a programme to pay the promising young professionals for life and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikyther to Candela in Italy or in the American Tulsia in Oklahoma.
